Bundle branch blocks

Left Bundle branch block

  • New onset LBBB is always pathological
  • Preexisting LBBB makes diagnosis difficult: Diagnosis of MI and left venctricular hypertrophy in patients with prexisting LBBB is difficult.
    Causes of LBBB:
  • MI
  • Hypertension
  • Aortic stenosis
  • Dilated Cardiomyopathy (Streching mechanically distrupts conduction)
  • Idiopathic fibrosis, digoxin toxicity, hyperkalemia
  • Cardiac scarring - disrupts conduction system
  • Cardiac infiltration - disrupts conduction system. (amyloidosis)

Sarcoidosis

[!TIP] Summary
Symmetrical Bilateral Hilar lymphadenopathy (BHL) is a characteristic feature of sarcoidosis and is usually asymptomatic.

  • Commoner in young adults.
  • The lungs are almost constantly affected (about 90% of cases) with bilateral pulmonary hilar lymph node involvement andpossible simultaneous involvement of the lungs.
  • These findings are localizedin interstitium adjacent to bronchioles as well as around and withinvessel walls, pleura, and connective tissue septa. There are Schaumann bodies (laminated concretions of calcium and protein) andasteroid elements (stellate inclusions within giant cells).
  • Multisystem inflammatory disease
  • Etiology unknown.
  • Relapses in most people
  • Lung involvement is commonest - Histology shows increased lymphocytes in alveolar walls and they can also be seen in bonchoalveolar lavage washings.
  • Extracardiac manifestations:
    • Skin - upto 30% - (lupus pernio, erythema nodosum) and eye -5% - (uveitis) are the commonest.
      • [[Sarcoidosis]] is the commonest cause of erythema nodosum.
    • CNS and cardiac are the most important.
  • Course of sarcoidosis is unaffected by pregnancy.
  • Valves: Valvular dysfunction
  • Renal involvement is uncommon but hypercalcemia and hypercalciuria and cause nephrocalcinosis and cause renal failure. Can also cause granulomatous tubulointerstitial nephritis.

  • Commonly diagnosed incidentally due to X ray findings.
    • However, pulmonary involvement can cause cough, exertional dyspnoea and chest discomfort.
    • Chest can be clear to auscultation.
    • Advanced stages will cause restrictive lung disease from fibrosis.
  • 20% have erythema nodosum.
  • Neurosarcoidosis :
    • meningoencephalitis
    • Cranial nerve palsy (esp. bilateral facial nerve palsy)
    • cord lesions

Prognosis

  • Stage 1 has very high (upto 90%) rates of spontaneous resolution.
  • Rate of resolution decreases rapidly with stage.
  • Relapses are common.

Management

  • Lung disease can resolve spontaneously and steroids improve radiologic appearance but not always lung function.
    • Therefore, systemic steroids are not regularly used for thoracic sarcoidosis.
  • Extrapulmonary sarcoisosis (CNS, Heart, Eye) and hypercalcemia are indications for systemic steroids.
  • "neuralgia" not "cephalgia" <- is a nerve pain rather than a headache
  • Occurs in elderly, hypertension is the main risk factor.
  • Treatment: Carbamazepine, surgical treatment is second line but more effective. (RF ablation)

$$ Therapeutic; index = \frac{LD_{50}}{ED_{50}} $$

  • Increased parasympathetic tone to the SA node and AV node -> (via hypersensitization of carotid sinus baroreceptors, central stimulation, increased vagal output, and possible potentiation of the effect of acetylcholine on the sinoatrial [SA] node) -> slowing the firing of the SA node and prolonging conduction at the atrioventricular (AV) node.
    Avoid in acute coronary syndrome
  • Downsloping ST depression - 'salvador dali' or 'reverse tick' appearance.
  • Especially hypokalemia or hypomagnesemia can potentiate toxicity.
  • Hypercalcemia can increase risk of toxicity. Hypocalcemia can nullify digoxin effects. -> maintain normal electrolyte levels.
    Acute toxicity is uncommon: Effects are
  • hypomagnesemia,
  • hypoxia will predispose to exagerrated action of digoxin. - Correct before administration.
  • Ventriular tachycardia
  • Ventricular ectopics (premature ventricular complexes)
  • Hyperkalemia (inhibition of Na/K Pump)
  • Side effect: Gynaecomastia
